      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
      "body" : "The Java 32-bit int matches 32-bit platforms (and the year 2038 problem).  64-bit platforms use a larger time_t data type.  Java dodged that bullet by using a long as the return for System.currentTimeMillis().  If you convert to int, you&#39;re re-introducing the year 2038 problem.  See <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Year_2038_problem#Solutions\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Year_2038_problem#Solutions</a>"
    }, {
